\begin_layout Standard
Over the 1975-2009 time period, according to demographic information acquired
 directly from the Colorado Division of Local Affairs, the population across
 all counties grew 93.4% (2,589,171 to 5,008,427).
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:County-Population-Dynamics"

\end_inset

 displays total population growth and the distribution of county population
 by year via violin plots.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Violin plots are essentially richer versions of box plots.
 The median value is given by the
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

heavy
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 dashed line, while the first and third quartile values are given by the
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

light
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 dashed lines.
 The sides of each
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

violin
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 are actually mirror images of the kernel density estimate.
 Thus, wide portions indicate regions in which many observations lie, while
 narrow portions indicate a relative paucity of observations.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 While the population has grown notably over time, the violin plots indicate
 that a relatively small portion of this growth is due to increases in the
 median county population.
 Rather, most of this growth is due to an increase in the size of the largest
 counties.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
