\begin_layout Standard
The Model 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "mod:Property-Tax-Subject-to-TABOR"

\end_inset

 governs the property tax revenue yield for each and every county subject
 to TABOR and the SLPTR in the absence of a local override.
 Given that the millage rate is subject to explicit voter approval and the
 assessment ratio is set at the state level, the economic activity within
 a county is the relevant action to focus on when questioning whether or
 not the composite limit will be breached.
 In other words, absent some sort of deBrucing vote which would allow for
 increased revenue, the growth in the value of the base should be compared
 to the composite limit to determine whether or not the limit will be breached.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The residential assessment rate was 12.86% in 1993.
 It fell four times during the study period to 10.36% (1995), 9.74% (1997),
 9.15% (2001), and 7.96% (2003).
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The value of the TABOR component of the constraint (second argument in
 the minimization function) utilizes CPI-U data from the Bureau of Labor
 Statistics and housing count information contained in the demographic profiles
 constructed by the Colorado Department of Local Affairs.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The query tool for the database containing demographic profiles by county
 is located here: https://dola.colorado.gov/demog_webapps/psParameters.jsf?counties
=T.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The market value of the base (both residential and non-residential) may
 itself be decomposed further.
