\backslash
_kern$
\end_layout

\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each choice features differing county-specific neighbor counts for each
 weight matrix.
 For example, for rook contiguity (
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$w
\backslash
_rook$
\end_layout

\end_inset

), five is the most frequent neighborhood size.
 This is in sharp contrast to the kernel matrix (
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$w
\backslash
_kern$
\end_layout

\end_inset

), which hase only six counties with a neighborhood of size five.
 The inconsistent neighborhood size distributions demonstrates the substantive
 variation in the definitions employed by each weight matrix and the reason
 for sensitivity to neighborhood definition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Local Indicators of Spatial Autocorrelation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are two primary measures used to establish spatial clustering for
 each weigh matrix/year combination.
 LMI measures the global spatial autocorrelation in an attribute 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$y$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 over a given neighborhood.
 Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "alg:Local-Moran's-I"

\end_inset

 is calculated for each county, 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$i$
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 LMI permits a kind of topological view of autocorrelation.
 Just as providing a single moment of a vector of values masks other distributio
nal characteristics of the data, providing only a single global parameter
 for spatial association masks regional dynamics.
 LMI reveals these dynamics by providing values for each spatial observation
 (e.g.
 county), thereby enabling the analyst to take note of patterns (e.g.
 fiscal clusters).
 LMI returns high values for a county when it is surrounded by
\emph on
 similar
\emph default
 values, and it returns low values when it is surrounded by
\emph on
 disimilar
\emph default
 values (Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:LMI-Values"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float model
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Local Moran's I (LMI)
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "alg:Local-Moran's-I"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset VSpace 10bp
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$$I_i=
\backslash
frac{
\backslash
sum_j z_i w_{i,j} z_j}{
\backslash
sum_i z_i^2}=
\backslash
frac{
\backslash
sum_j (y_i-
\backslash
bar y)w_{i,j}(y_j-
\backslash
bar y)}{
\backslash
sum_i(y_i-
\backslash
bar y)^2}$$
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Local Moran's I Values
\end_layout

\end_inset

Interpretation of Local Moran's I Values
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:LMI-Values"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
centerline{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/Moran_colors.png
	lyxscale 20
	width 120text%

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As noted by Anselin
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Anselin1995"

\end_inset

, the interpretation of LMI is insufficient for a comprehensive knowledge
 of the clustering behavior of spatially related activities.
 It can provide an analyst with knowledge of the existence of clusters,
 but it does not provide information about the type of clustering.
 In this regard, GOG (Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "alg:Getis-Ord-G"

\end_inset

) is a natural complement.
 It is also calculated for each spatial feature (e.g.
 county).
 In contrast to LMI, GOG returns high values when
\emph on
 high
\emph default
 values are clustered and low values when
\emph on
 low
\emph default
 values are clustered (Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:GOG-Values"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float model
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Getis & Ord's G* (GOG)
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "alg:Getis-Ord-G"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset VSpace 10bp
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$$G_i(d)=
\backslash
frac{
\backslash
sum_j w_{i,j} (d) y_j - W_i
\backslash
bar y(i)}{s(i)
\backslash
{[(n-1) S_{1i} - W_i^2]/(n-2)
\backslash
}^{(1/2)}},j
\backslash
neq i$$
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Getis & Ord's G* Values
\end_layout

\end_inset

Interpretation of Getis & Ord's G* Values
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:GOG-Values"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
centerline{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/GO_colors.png
	lyxscale 20
	width 120text%

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If one were to rely solely on LMI, the clustering of low revenue capacity
 would be indistinguishable from the clustering of high revenue capacity.
 If one were to rely solely on GOG, it would not be possible to detect unusual
 patterns of discontinuity.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Unusual patterns would be those discontinuities that were beyond those which
 would occur with a random shuffling of values.
 In other words, they would be systemic patterns of disimilarity, also known
 as negative spatial autocorrelation.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This would render the detection of local anomolies more difficult, and
 in turn, the identification of spatial non-stationarity.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Stationarity is the same concept in a spatial context as it is the more
 widespread temporal context.
 In time series, the joint distribution of observations must be invariant
 to a time shift to be considered strictly stationary.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

A time series 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

${r_t}$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is said to be
\emph on
 strictly stationary
\emph default
 if the joint distribution of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$(r_{t_1}, ...
 , r_{t_k})$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is identical to that of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$(r_{t_1 + t}, ...
 , r_{t_k + t})$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$t$
\end_layout

\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$k$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is an arbitrary positive integer and 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$(t_1, ...
 ,t_k)$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is a collection of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$k$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 positive integers.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Weak stationarity just requires that the mean of the reference observation
 and the covariance between the reference and a lag of arbitrary size must
 be invariant to a time shift.
 In effect, the observations share a common mean, and there is some fixed
 amount of noise.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quotation
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

A time series 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

${r_t}$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is
\emph on
 weakly stationary
\emph default
 if (a) 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$E(r_t) =
\backslash
mu$
\end_layout

\end_inset

, which is a constant, and (b) 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$
\backslash
mathrm{Cov}(r_t,r_{t-l})=
\backslash
gamma_l$
\end_layout

\end_inset

, which only depends on 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$l$
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Tsay2005"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
One may think of spatial stationarity in the same way, accept that lags
 are not uni-directional as in the time series case.
 Rather, lags extend in all directions.
 In a time series, the observation in the preceding time period is a first
 order temporal lag.
 In a neighborhood defined by queen contiguity (see Subsection 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Weight-Matrices"

\end_inset

), all of the jurisdictions that touch the primary jurisdiction are first
 order spatial lags.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Therefore, to gain a complete picture of spatial patterns in revenue yield
 and capacity, we must use both LMI and GOG.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The spatio-temporal plots below display spatial clustering activity over
 time for each weight matrix.
 The first collection (Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:LMI-Plots"

\end_inset

) features clustering as a measured by LMI while the second (Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:GOG-Plots"

\end_inset

) features GOG.
 In both collections, the first plot matrix displays clustering of revenue
 yield (per capita revenue) and revenue capacity (per capita annual payroll).
 While the intensity of clustering does vary to some extent across different
 weight matrices (as indicated by varying color intensity), the general
 patterns persist.
\end_layout

