\begin_layout Subsection
Results
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Clearly, there are challenges associated with the presentation of 58 models.
 As mentioned above, however, our overarching concern is consistency.
 To what extent do the models tell the same story.
 With this in mind, we are afforded some flexibility in presentation.
 A graphical approach is taken here.
 Furthermore, a summary view of the LISA models is provided, each view of
 which shares averages of coefficient estimates, p-values, and model fit
 for all five weight matrices presented.
 In all of the visualizations that follow, three interpretations apply:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Coefficient estimates are represented by the y-axis value;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$p$
\end_layout

\end_inset

-values are represented by color of the bubble
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A diverging color scale is used.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$p$
\end_layout

\end_inset

-values below 0.1 are a shade of blue, while values above 0.1 are a shade
 of red.
\end_layout

\end_inset

; and,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Model fit (
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$R^2$
\end_layout

\end_inset

) is represented by the size of the bubble.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Baseline Estimation with Pooled Ordinary Least Squares
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As will become apparent, the pooled OLS models provide a view of a counterintuit
ive, yet relatively consistent, narrative.
 While the COTEL intensity measure (
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$intensity
\backslash
_stock$
\end_layout

\end_inset

) has the expected negative and statistically significant effect on revenue
 yield (
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$pcrev$
\end_layout

\end_inset

), higher values of the intensity measure are consistently associated with
 higher levels of fiscal capacity (
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$pcap$
\end_layout

\end_inset

).
 This is a curious result that directly challenges the notion that COTELs
 limit the fiscal capacity of a given county.
 Furthermore, the same revenue yield relationship holds for the ratio of
 residential and non-residential property (
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$prop
\backslash
_ratio$
\end_layout

\end_inset

) used to capture the impact of the Gallagher Amendment (the Gallagher Ratio).
 Again, higher relative amounts of residential property are associated with
 lower revenue yields.
 This accords with intuition to the extent that GA is designed to limit
 residential property tax liability.
 Fiscal capacity, on the other hand, is higher in counties which have higher
 relative levels of residential property in the assessment base.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Pooled OLS Results
\end_layout

\end_inset

Pooled OLS Results - Fiscal Capacity (
\emph on
left
\emph default
) & Revenue Yield(
\emph on
right
\emph default
)
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Pooled-OLS-Results"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/converge_pooled_ols.png
	width 100text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note also the large disparity in model fit across the two models.
 This is a persistent character of this analysis - all of the revenue yield
 models explain a larger portion of the variance than do their fiscal capacity
 counterparts.
 This is perhaps unsurprising.
 The impact of institutions and economic changes on revenue yield is much
 more direct than is the impact on fiscal capacity.
 Complete identification of this indirect linkage can be pursued in future
 research.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Evaluating the Impact on Fiscal Clustering with Local Indicators of Spatial
 Autocorrelation (LISAs)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the LISAs as dependents provides some notion of how the variables
 in the model impact spatial clustering of revenue yield and fiscal capacity.
 Counties experiencing higher levels of COTEL intensity are expected to
 converge in the revenue yield and fiscal capacity measures.
 In effect, the COTELs are expected to retard their revenue growth, which
 will create a wedge between constrained and unconstrained counties.
 It has already been shown that spatial clustering of fiscal behavior occurs,
 so this wedge is expected to be spatially relevant.
 The visualization of these results employs averages across the five weight
 matrices used in this analysis (see Subsecton 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Weight-Matrices"

\end_inset

).
 Again, this is to limit the sensitivity of interpretation to choice of
 the local neighborhood, 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$W$
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The results of the LISA models can be placed in context by getting a sense
 of the distribution of clustering values.
 Figure X shows the kernel densities of each LISA dependent variable.
 They are grouped by clustering concept (e.g.
 Local Moran's I, or LMI) and clustering value (e.g.
 per capita revenue, or 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$pcrev$
\end_layout

\end_inset

).
 Within each group, the densities are shown for all five weight matrix definitio
ns used in this analysis (see Subsection 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Weight-Matrices"

\end_inset

).
 Take note of the reported standard deviations.
 They range from 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$
\backslash
sigma = 0.56$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$
\backslash
sigma = 2.47$
\end_layout

\end_inset

, although the latter is a bit of an outlier.
 The median is 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$
\backslash
sigma = 1.16$
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Distribution of Clustering Values
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Distribution-of-Clustering-Values"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
centerline{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/cluster_wt_dist.png
	lyxscale 50
	width 95page%

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To reiterate, high values of LMI indicate the clustering of similar values,
 while low values indicate the clustering of disimilar values.
 In other words, high values of LMI can indicate the presence of a local
 neighborhood of counties characterized by either high revenue yield/fiscal
 capacity or low revenue yield/fiscal capacity.
 In contrast, high values of GOG indicate clustering of high values, while
 low values of GOG indicate clustering of low values.
 Thus, LMI reveals more about the strength of clustering while GOG reveals
 more about the type of clustering.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
LISA Results
\end_layout

\end_inset

LISA Results - Revenue Yield (
\emph on
left
\emph default
) & Fiscal Capacity (
\emph on
right
\emph default
)
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:LISA-Results"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
centerline{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/converge_LISAs.png
	lyxscale 80
	width 120text%
	rotateAngle 90

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When controlling for other factors, COTEL intensity (
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$intensity
\backslash
_stock$
\end_layout

\end_inset

) has very limited impact on the clustering of revenue yield (
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$pcrev$
\end_layout

\end_inset

).
 Said differently, if a county is highly constrained, the constraint is
 not a significant driver of the clustering that already exists.
 This is interesting because one could reasonably expect that the inflexibility
 of achievable expenditures in the constrained county would force convergence
 in fiscal behavior, thereby taking jurisdictional idiosyncrasies out of
 the siting equation and reinforcing similar revenue preferences in the
 local neighborhood.
 It is possible that collaborative efforts in the local neighborhood to
 provide wide area services free up enough revenue to still allow for some
 base level of distinction.
 Further, COTEL intensity has a rather ambivalent relationship with fiscal
 capacity (
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$pcap$
\end_layout

\end_inset

) clustering values (GOG), which speaks little to the idea that higher levels
 of COTEL constraints are related to clustering of low values of fiscal
 capacity.
 In other words, this view provides no support for the hypothesis that COTELs
 ultimately limit fiscal capacity for low-income jurisdictions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the other hand, the Gallagher Ratio (
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$prop
\backslash
_ratio$
\end_layout

\end_inset

) behaves precisely as we would expect from a revenue yield perspective.
 Insofar as it increases the strength of clustering (higher values of LMI)
 and decreases the values assoicated with said clustering (low values of
 GOG), the evidence suggests that the measure is a limiting factor on revenue
 yield in the local neighborhood.
 On the fiscal capacity side, the Gallagher Ratio is neither statistically
 or substantively relevant.
 In both the revenue yield and fiscal capacity models, the model fit is
 modest at best (particularly with respect to the latter) and categorically
 lower than the fit of any other model considered in this chapter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Incorporating the Local Neighborhood with Spatial Lags
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Repeated SLM analysis allows us to incorporate the local neighborhood explicitly
 because the spatial lag of the dependent variable is the weighted average
 of the dependent variable value in the neighboring jurisdictions.
 Evaluating annual cross-sections is useful insofar as it provides a view
 of the variation in regressor impact over time, both in magnitude and significa
nce.
 The non-trivial downsides are two-fold:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Repeated cross-sections do not permit control of year-specific factors;
 and,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
To the extent that deBrucing is an ongoing phenomenon, there is temporal
 variance in the sample properties.
 The characteristics of the counties, namely the capacity of COTELs to constrain
 a given jurisdiction, are changing over time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a consequence, the technique can only be useful in this context as a
 complementary component in a larger analysis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
SLM - Revenue Yield
\end_layout

\end_inset

Spatial Lag Models by Year - Revenue Yield (
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$pcrev$
\end_layout

\end_inset

)
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:SLM-Rev"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
centerline{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/converge_slm_rev.png
	lyxscale 80
	width 85page%

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Note: the single red data points in the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$pcap$
\end_layout

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$prop
\backslash
_ratio$
\end_layout

\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$vac_rate$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 subplots are only artifacts of the plotting function.
 As can be seen in the color bar, the range of p-values for these variables
 is entirely below 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$p$=0.1
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The final version of this graphic will remedy this issue with post-hoc
 adjsutment of the an SVG version of the plot.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With respect to revenue yield, both COTEL intensity (
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$intensity
\backslash
_stock$
\end_layout

\end_inset

) and the Gallagher Ratio (
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$prop
\backslash
_ratio$
\end_layout

\end_inset

) accord with the pooled OLS results.
 They both materially decrease the revenue per capita in the county, even
 after controlling for the revenue dynamics in the local neighborhood.
 In other words, these are reductions over and above the preferences that
 may be shared with neighboring jurisdictions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The interesting dynamic revealed by the repeated cross-sectional approach
 is that COTEL intensity appears to get less significant over time, both
 in statistical and substantive terms.
 In contrast, the Gallagher Ratio is doing precisely the opposite.
 This could indicate either a shift in the composition of counties subject
 to binding COTEL constraints or a shift in the composition of the property
 assessment base (or both).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Evaluating fiscal capacity with the repeated SLM approach reveals the tenuous
 nature of any direct connection between our COTEL variables and per capita
 annual payroll.
 COTEL intensity and the Gallagher Ratio are both statististically insignificant
 in every single year.
 For the most part, COTEL intensity is also substantively insignificant
 while the Gallagher Ratio demonstrates substantial variation in magnitude.
 With respect to the latter, it is also worth noting that the sign of the
 Gallagher Ratio estimate remains at least directionally consistent with
 the pooled OLS run.
 Even when controlling for the other factors, the underlying positive relationsh
ip between per capita annual payroll and the Gallagher Ratio.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
SLM - Fiscal Capacity
\end_layout

\end_inset

Spatial Lag Models by Year - Fiscal Capacity
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:SLM-econ"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
centerline{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/converge_slm_econ.png
	lyxscale 80
	width 85page%

\end_inset


