\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Capturing Temporal Dependency with Fixed Effects
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Pivoting from the modeling of spatial to temporal dependency, it is possible
 to control for county-specific unobservables that may obscure the mechanism
 by which changes in COTEL intensity (
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$intensity
\backslash
_stock$
\end_layout

\end_inset

) and the Gallagher Ratio (
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$prop
\backslash
_ratio$
\end_layout

\end_inset

) effect changes in revenue yield and fiscal capacity.
 The panel model results plot for revenue yield reveals a consistent theme
 for most variables, although the permitting rate (
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$permit
\backslash
_rate$
\end_layout

\end_inset

) sign has switched from the OLS flight.
 Both COTEL intensity and the Gallagher Ratio are modestly depressing forces
 on revenue yield in a given county.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Fixed Effect Estimation
\end_layout

\end_inset

Fixed Effect Model Results - Revenue Yield (
\emph on
left
\emph default
) & Fiscal Capacity (
\emph on
right
\emph default
)
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:FE-Results"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/converge_fe_panel.png
	lyxscale 80
	width 120text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The raw coefficient estimates are provided in Tables
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:FE-Rev-Table"

\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:FE-Econ-Table"

\end_inset

 .
 If the estimates are standardized to reflect the impact sizes as a multiple
 of the standard deviation, a one standard deviation shift in COTEL intensity
 accounts for a shift in revenue yield of approximately 4% of one standard
 deviation in revenue yield (
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$pcrev$
\end_layout

\end_inset

).
 The parallel impact for the Gallagher Ratio is 9%.
 These figures are roughly three times as large as those reported in the
 pooled OLS model, and twenty times as large as those reported in the spatial
 lag models (on average).
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Note that this is the average response to a shift of a single standard deviation
 across the models for all years.
 Thus, this effect would not necessarily scale linearly,
\emph on
even if the impact of a change in COTEL variables were consistent through
 the entire range of COTEL values
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

