</lyxtabular>

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second step of this protocol leverages the fact that our primary concern
 is the impact of COTEL intensity on fiscal behavior.
 Consequently, only those dimensions that are actually affected by TEL impositio
n are retained.
 In other words, inclusion in the final model is determined by whether or
 not the expenditure category has a meaningful relationship with COTEL intensity
, as indicated by a series of bivariate regressions.
 The procedure for selection of subgroups is discussed in Paragraph 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "par:Selection-of-Expenditure-Subgroups"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Selection of Expenditure Subgroups
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "par:Selection-of-Expenditure-Subgroups"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To select from the subgroups identified in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Subgroups-for-Track-1a"

\end_inset

, there are two properties that must be identified:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The extent of variation in each subgroup's proportional contribution to
 the entire expenditure portfolio.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The amount of each subgroup's variation
\emph on
 that can be associated with variance in COTEL intensity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first conditions the findings of the second.
 Though in reality the impact of COTEL intensity has been evaluated for
 all subgroups, those subgroups that vary the least are not as desirable.
 The variation in subgroup contribution can be seen in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Distribution-of-Subgroup-Proportions"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Expenditure Subgroup Proportions
\end_layout

\end_inset

Distribution of Subgroup Proportional Contribution to Total Expenditures
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Distribution-of-Subgroup-Proportions"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/exp_subgroup_dist.png
	lyxscale 80
	width 100text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To associate movement in each subgroup as a function of COTEL intensity,
 a series of models have been run on two different COTEL intensity concepts:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Intensity
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

flow is the gap between allowable revenue yield under TABOR/SLPTR and that
 which would be possible based upon economic conditions within a county.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Intensity
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

stock is the cumulative impact of intensity flow.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For each intensity concept, two sets of models tested association with transform
ed versions of the subgroup proportions.
 These transforms, demeaning and standardization, were employed to capture
 only within county variation due to COTEL intensity.
 As can be seen in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Intensity-vs-Exp-Subgroup"

\end_inset

, both sets of models yielded similar results.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
COTEL Impact on Expenditure Subgroups
\end_layout

\end_inset

Impact of COTEL Intensity on Individual Expenditure Subgroups
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Intensity-vs-Exp-Subgroup"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
centerline{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/COTEL_intensity_vs_exp_subgroups.png
	lyxscale 70
	width 120text%

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The coefficient estimates are captured as the y-axis position, the fit (
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$R^2$
\end_layout

\end_inset

) by the size of the bubble, and the statistical significance by the color.
 As can be seen, intensity flow had negligible impacts on the expenditure
 subgroups.
 The intensity stock models identified three subgroups of interest: health
 and social services, public safety, and public works.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is interesting to note that the two dimension reduction procedures (PCA
 and regression selection) highlight different aspects of the fiscal portfolio.
 The variation in public works-related expenditures is a common theme, as
 is health and social services.
 However, there is some disagreement in the public safety area.
 This underscores the need for three flights of models using the distances
 calculated via Track 1, Track 1a, and Track 2.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In all Tracks, the final component dimension is the proportion of all government
 expenditures in the county that are specifically attributed to the county
 government (
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$cty
\backslash
_exp
\backslash
_prop$
\end_layout

\end_inset

).
 To the extent that counties may vary in their propensity to leverage municipali
ties or school districts for the delivery of services, this is a material
 dimension that will lead to differing behaviors across counties.
 As such, it is included in the type definition array.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Identifying County Expenditure Types
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A central pillar of this analysis involves the capacity to assign types
 to individual counties.
 Which rule should be used to group counties when no a priori classification
 information exists? What is required is a classification scheme that is
 emergent, conditional on the data.
 The approach employed here is
\emph on
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$k$
\end_layout

\end_inset

-means clustering
\emph default
.
 The technique, implemented via the expression in Algorithm 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "alg:k-Means-Clustering"

\end_inset

, minimizes the total distance between members of the same cluster (within-group
 variance).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float algorithm
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$k$
\end_layout

\end_inset

-Means Clustering
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "alg:k-Means-Clustering"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset VSpace 10bp
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$$
\backslash
mathrm{argmin}_S
\backslash
sum_{i=1}^k
\backslash
sum_{x_j
\backslash
in S_i}
\backslash
| x_j-
\backslash
mu_i
\backslash
|^2$$
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset VSpace 10bp
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The expression minimizes the sum of all distances between each point, 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$x_j$
\end_layout

\end_inset

, and its associated centroid, 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$
\backslash
mu_i$
\end_layout

\end_inset

, within each cluster, 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$S_i$
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 There are 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$k$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 clusters; 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$k$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is given as a parametric input.
 The expression is referred to as the minimum sum of squared residuals (SSM).
 Insofar as this approach defines groups without pre-existing classification
 attributes, it is considered a member of the
\emph on
 unsupervised learning
\emph default
 class of estimators.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The definition of position is of central importance, and it varies with
 context.
 In the current case, each point (
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$x_j$
\end_layout

\end_inset

) represents the fiscal position of a county in one of the fiscal spaces
 defined in Subsection 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Defining-Fiscal-Space"

\end_inset

.
 In a well behaved case, in which the clusters are reasonably well defined,
 the clustering algorithm returns groups as seen in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Well-Behaved-Clusters"

\end_inset

.
 Our fiscal position data is not nearly as well behaved, but 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$k$
\end_layout

\end_inset

-means clustering still provides a framework for cluster selection.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Well Behaved Clusters
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Well-Behaved-Clusters"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/kmeans_ideal.png
	lyxscale 70
	width 100text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Group membership is defined here by color.
 The centroids of each group, or cluster, are represented by the large markers
 of each group's color.
 Note that the centroid markers
\emph on
 do not represent observations.

\emph default
 Rather, they are calculated measures of within-cluster central tendency.
 The image is attributed to the documentation of the 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "scikit-learn library"
target "http://scikit-learn.org/stable/"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From an operational perspective, the clustering analysis was performed based
 upon fiscal positions in the PCA space.
 The reasons for this are two-fold.
 First, the dimension reduction techniques (PCA and regression filtering)
 allow us to distill down to three dimensions, which facilitates visualization.
 As it turns out, visualization is a very useful way of checking the face
 validity of the algorithm's output.
 Second, PCA is preferable relative to the regression filtering approach
 because it retains nearly all of the information in the original set.
 This is because the new dimensions are just complex combinations of the
 old dimensions, and the first three components explain 75.3% of the variation
 in the data (Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Variation-in-Exp-PCA"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Principal Components of Expenditure
\end_layout

\end_inset

Variation in Principal Components of the Expenditure Portfolio
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Variation-in-Exp-PCA"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/exp_pca.png
	lyxscale 80
	width 100text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall that the major drawback of the PCA approach is the interpretation
 of movement along one of the compound dimensions that remain.
 However, if all that matters for this particular operation is the proximity
 of fiscal positions across counties, interpretation of the linear combinations
 of underlying dimensions is not the principal concern.
 Consequently, the space defined by PCA is unambiguously superior to the
 space defined by regression filtering for the purpose of identifying clusters
 of county fiscal preferences.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Choosing the Appropriate Number of Clusters 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$k$
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is important to reiterate that the use of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$k$
\end_layout

\end_inset

-means clustering requires the number of groups, 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$k$
\end_layout

\end_inset

, to be a parametric input.
 Therefore, there is a certain amount of subjectivity involved, because
 the optimal value of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$k$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is unknown.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
If, for example, one were to choose 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$k$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 such that the aggregate distance between points within each cluster was
 minimized, one would find that 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$k
\backslash
to n$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$n$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is the number of observations.
 In other words, each cluster would shrink to contain only a single observation.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This subjectivity is particularly prominent when group boundaries are not
 clean.
 The fiscal positions of Colorado counties in 1975 are displayed in Figure
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Fiscal-Positions-1975"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Fiscal Positions - 1975
\end_layout

\end_inset

Fiscal Positions of Counties in Colorado in 1975
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Fiscal-Positions-1975"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
centerline{
\end_layout

\end_inset


