	filename figures/fisc_pos1975.png
	lyxscale 70
	width 120text%

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Note that the fiscal positions are not as well-behaved as the ideal case
 above.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To lessen the influence of the subjectivity in selecting the number of groups,
 this analysis tested a range of values for 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$k$
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 This allows one to evaluate the impact on SSM of additional clusters.
 That being said, variance in group count, 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$k$
\end_layout

\end_inset

, is a useful but insufficient means for identifying the correct clustering
 profile.
 On the one hand, SSM is
\emph on
always
\emph default
 a non-increasing function of the number of groups 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$k$
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, it is simply desirable to minimize the number of required
 groups because evaluating the dynamics of a group is less than useful if
 it has only a few members.
 To mitigate the tension between these two desirable properties and determine
 the number of clusters to be used for econometric analysis, three tests
 augmented visual inspection of clustering:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The first method evaluates the marginal contribution to
\emph on
 between-cluster variation
\emph default
 of each cluster.
 The technique seeks to understand movement in the ratio of between-cluster
 variation to total variation in the sample.
 The desirable number of groups is then the value,
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$k$
\end_layout

\end_inset

, at which the ratio increase over the interval 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$[k-1,k]$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is significantly higher than the ratio increase over the interval 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$[k,k+1]$
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The second method evaluates the marginal contribution to
\emph on
 within-cluster variation
\emph default
 of each cluster.
 As previously indicated, this function decreases with increases in the
 number of groups 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$k$
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 When intersected with the first method, the result is a balancing of separation
 across clusters and similarity within clusters.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The third method is a popular selection mechanism known as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

silhouette score
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 In this case, the number of clusters is identified by maximizing the aggregate
 distances of observations in cluster 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$i$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 from the centroid of all groups 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$j$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (where 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$i
\backslash
neq j$
\end_layout

\end_inset

),
\emph on
 relative to the points' distance from their own centroid in group
\emph default
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$i$
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The test ensemble suggested that the optimal cluster count, 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$k$
\end_layout

\end_inset

, lies on the interval 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$[5,8]$
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Within these bounds, selection proceeded via visual inspection of the clusterin
g outcomes at each value of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$k$
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Ultimately, five clusters were found to provide the cleanest separation
 of groups.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Fiscal Clusters
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$k=5$
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

Fiscal Clusters
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$k=5$
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
