}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Caveat Emptor
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The last view considered prior to modeling is the
\emph on
 within-county
\emph default
 variation in distance to the associated centroid.
 In Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:cty-clust-dist-var"

\end_inset

, the distribution of cluster distances across years is displayed by county.
 On the positive side, it reinforces the idea that counties within a cluster
 can behave quite differently over time.
 The analysis seeks to leverage this variation in behavior to understand
 the impact of COTELs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Within-County Variation of Distance to Cluster
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:cty-clust-dist-var"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/clustDist_var_cty.png
	lyxscale 50
	width 90text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The counties are colored by type.
 Note that these distances are not measured from the same location, but
 rather the location of the centroid of each county's associated type.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, this view does some violence to the idea of constant covariance
 in within-cluster expenditure preferences.
 First, while we seek to identify within-cluster differences associated
 with COTELs, other differences capture inherent disimilarity as well.
 Second, there is an assumption that counties do not change types, but it
 is plausible that the variation seen in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:cty-clust-dist-var"

\end_inset

 would lead to different types at different times.
 Again, if this is due to COTELs, this is a useful finding.
 If it is due to other factors, it again highlights inherent disimilarity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, some weaknesses of the constant covariance approach certainly exist,
 but as discussed in Subsection 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Typification-Reasonable"

\end_inset

, it is likely to be a less costly assumption than alternative assumptions
 that can be made.
 In general,
\emph on
 there does not exist a unique approach that may reveal the fundamental
 nature of the phenomenon in isolation.

\emph default
 Hoover reflects usefully on the general selection of an estimation approach:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quotation
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

[T]he thorough-going optimization implicit in new classicism suggests that
 everything depends on everything else, not just in theory, but in practice.
 [...] Thus, theory presents us with some a priori (in the sense of not
\emph on
 currently
\emph default
 questioned) restrictions on empirical investigation; while the empirical
 results help us generate beliefs (or new theories) which are prior to further
 investigations.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Hoover1994"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In other words, we restrict the lens through which we view the observable
 implications of some unseen phenomenon.
 While the lens may be defensible, each choice suffers from the weakness
 of our a priori belief about how said lens ought to be defined.
 No single view should be evaluated as having incorporated the full complexity
 of the system under study.
 Rather, we take simplified cuts at the data generating process, and converge
 on 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

reality
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, with confidence increasing in the number of supporting analytic outcomes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given the basic establishment of statistical identification, it is important
 to consider the impact of the boundaries imposed by a given method (e.g.
 constant covariance).
 The concern, from a utility standpoint, is whether or not the boundaries
 are responsible for driving measurement outcomes, as opposed to the underlying
 data generating process.
 Indeed, it was with this liability in mind that the decision was made to
 leverage data driven classification in the first place.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$k$
\end_layout

\end_inset

-means clustering does take a single parameter, 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$k$
\end_layout

\end_inset

, but it does not otherwise impose any distributional assumptions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the end, the approach taken here must not be viewed as a substitute for
 the views that would be revealed by other approaches, inclusive of those
 considered in Subsection 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Typification-Reasonable"

\end_inset

.
 Rather, this approach, unique to the best of the author's knowledge, provides
 an important view of the underlying data that should be considered in a
 comprehensive assessment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
What is the Expected Impact of TELs?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The frame for this analysis is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

expenditure wedge
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Do constrained jurisdictions deflect from their preferred expenditure bundles?
 It is hypothesized that any such deflection would be in the direction of
 providing a minimum bundle of services, and it is expected that the minimum
 bundle reflects a fairly consistent set of needs for any general purpose
 jurisdiction (Model 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "mod:exp_impact"

\end_inset

).
 Therefore, paring down to the minimum bundle would limit the capacity of
 a given jurisdiction to distinguish itself from other jurisdictions.
 It is further expected that the impact of this convergence will be strongest
 in low-income jurisdictions, where resources are already constrained.
 The work of Mullins and Joyce
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Joyce_Mullins1991"

\end_inset

 has revealed that binding TELs are associated with shifts of expenditure
 responsibility to the state level, which also promotes uniformity in service
 delivery (or at least in the resources allocated).
 This study evaluates what counties in Colorado do with the remaining resources.
 What does their expenditure profile look like when TELs have taken effect?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float model
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
COTELs and Expenditure Behavior
\end_layout

\end_inset

What is the Nature of COTEL Impact on Expenditure Behavior?
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "mod:exp_impact"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset VSpace 10bp
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Expenditure
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Differentiation =
\emph on
f
\emph default
(Resources to Cover the Minimum Service Bundle, Excess Resources)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset VSpace 5bp
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset VSpace 5bp
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Resources
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

to
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Cover
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

the
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Minimum
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Service
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Bundle =
\emph on
f
\emph default
(Demographic Factors, Geographic Environment)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Excess
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Resources =
\emph on
f
\emph default
(Revenue Base Dynamics, Institutional Restrictions on Revenue)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset VSpace 10bp
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In effect, the model in this study suggests that institutional restrictions
 on revenue (e.g.
 tax and expenditure limitations) restrict the resources available to cover
 services that would allow a given jurisdiction to differentiate itself
 from others.
 In reality, this is a gross simplification.
 There is no natural boundary between revenues used to cover basic services
 and those used to cover the additional services preferred by constituents.
 In general, this model suggests convergence in expenditure behavior would
 stem from the imposition of COTELs.
\end_layout

\end_inset

If expenditure behavior shifts, a wedge is thrown between the realized and
 preferred tax-expenditure bundle for a given county.
 For prospective residents, the choice set is more limited, and the properties
 that may have drawn them to a particular county are less of a factor.
 For existing residents, an artificial difference has been created between
 the initial, expected utility that factored into the decision to site in
 the county and the realized utility after the expenditure shift has occurred.
 In practice, this may or may not lead to a reshuffling for those residents
 that can afford to move.
 Those that cannot simply experience a loss in utility.
 Furthermore, if the choices in close proximity lose some of their differentiati
on, the cost of relocating to a more 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

desirable
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 county increases.
 In any event, understanding the impact of loss in differentiation is important
 for a comprehensive view of COTEL impact.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Do TELs Shift Patterns of Expenditure?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our primary inquiry centers on whether or not the distance of a given county
 from the average preference position of counties of that type can be explained
 to some meaningful degree by the intensity of the COTEL constraint acting
 on said county.
 In measuring this, it is important to control for confounding economic
 processes that may impact cluster distance.
 These economic processes may occur in both the current observation's county,
 and the adjoining counties that may share bases of economic activity.
 In other words, the model must account for both the primary county, and
 the counties in the local neighborhood.
 Model 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "mod:clust-dist-model"

\end_inset

 captures this process in a general way.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Recall that the proportion of expenditures from all governments in the county
 that are undertaken by the county government (
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$cty
\backslash
_exp
\backslash
_prop$
\end_layout

\end_inset

) is included to speak the scope of county government application, but it
 is modeled as part of the definition of county positions used to measure
 cluster distance.
 To include it here as a regressor would be to capture the equation in both
 the dependent and independent sides of the specification.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float model
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Determinants of Cluster Distance
\end_layout

\end_inset

Modeling Determinants of Cluster Distance
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "mod:clust-dist-model"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset VSpace 10bp
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$$y_{it} =
\backslash
underbrace{W y_{i_-,t}
\backslash
Gamma_1}_{(1)} +
\backslash
underbrace{
\backslash
sum_{l=1}^L y_{i,t-l}
\backslash
Gamma_2}_{(2)} +
\backslash
underbrace{Z_{i,t}
\backslash
beta}_{(3)} +
\backslash
epsilon_{i,t}$$
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$$Z_{i,t}
\backslash
beta =
\backslash
underbrace{W X_{i_-,t}
\backslash
beta_1}_{
\backslash
text{(3a)}} +
\backslash
underbrace{X_{i,t}
\backslash
beta_2}_{
\backslash
text{(3b)}} +
\backslash
underbrace{X_t
\backslash
beta_3}_{
\backslash
text{(3c)}}$$
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset VSpace 10bp
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$y_{i,t}$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is the dependent variable (
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$clust
\backslash
_dist$
\end_layout

\end_inset

), the distance of county 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$i$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$t$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 from the centroid of its cluster (a.k.a.
 cluster distance).
 Note that 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$y_{i_-,t}$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 denotes the cluster distance of each county 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$j$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$t$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$i
\backslash
neq j$
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$W$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is the weight matrix that defines the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

local neighborhood
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$
\backslash
Gamma$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 represents the coefficients of autoregressive terms.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$
\backslash
Gamma_1$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is for the spatially autoregressive effect, while 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$
\backslash
Gamma_2$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is for the temporally autoregressive effect.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$Z_{i,t}$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is a vector of regressors that includes the primary variables of interest,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$intensity
\backslash
_stock$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$prop
\backslash
_ratio$
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 These include factors from the local neighborhood, county-specific factors,
 and statewide factors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$
\backslash
epsilon_{i,t}$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is the error term.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The model can be broken down into components, each of which are numbered
 above.
 The top line equation captures spatial autoregression in cluster distance
 (1), temporal autoregression in cluster distance (2), and forces acting
 on the primary county at time 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$t$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (3).
 The second equation unpacks term 3.
 It captures select properties of counties in the local neighborhood (3a),
 county-specific properties (3b), and statewide variables (3c).
 The breakdown of variables in term 3 are as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Term
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

3a includes total expenditures (
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$EXP
\backslash
_TOTAL$
\end_layout

\end_inset

), population growth in the preceding year (
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$pop
\backslash
_growth$
\end_layout

\end_inset

), and the ratio of vacant housing units to total housing units (
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$vac
\backslash
_rate$
\end_layout

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Term
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

3b includes total expenditures (
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$EXP
\backslash
_TOTAL$
\end_layout

\end_inset

), population growth in the preceding year (
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$pop
\backslash
_growth$
\end_layout

\end_inset

), intergovernmental revenue per capita (
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$pcintgov$
\end_layout

\end_inset

), total revenue per capita (
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

