\begin_layout Standard
Our measure of similarity, or disimilarity as the case may be, is 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$clust
\backslash
_dist$
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 It proves to be useful, but it would be more so if it varied over a greater
 range.
 Marginal impacts of regressors are easier to identify when they are associated
 with larger absolute spans in the range of dependent values.
 If a given dependent variable takes one of only two values, the contributions
 of each regressor is more difficult to distinguish relative to the case
 in which a dependent variable
\emph on
 with the same support
\emph default
 (that is, the same range of feasible values) takes any one of 100 values.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It would be interesting to know if the correlation dynamics shift based
 upon the definition of cluster distance (Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Var-Variation-Alt-Dist"

\end_inset

).
 Recall that while all three distances are 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$
\backslash
