\begin_layout Subsection
Cross-Sectional Models
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:ExpDiv-Cross-Sectional-Models"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Model 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "mod:clust-dist-model"

\end_inset

 presents a view of the world that represents the a priori belief of the
 author with respect to cross-sectional action in county fiscal behavior.
 Given that county groups are not defined spatially, and thus members are
 often not close to each other, it seems quite plausible that the factors
 that may lead a county to part ways with group behavior are spatial factors
 which would not be shared across all members of the group.
 Thus, it is expected that spatial dependency, either through lags or errors,
 would need to be integrated into the analysis.
 The abstract and operational versions of this view are provided in Model
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "mod:Cross-Sectional-Estimation-of-Exp-Diverg"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float model
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
SLM - Expenditure Divergence
\end_layout

\end_inset

Cross-Sectional Estimation of Expenditure Divergence
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "mod:Cross-Sectional-Estimation-of-Exp-Diverg"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset VSpace 10bp
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$$y_i =
\backslash
underbrace{W y_{i_-}
\backslash
Gamma}_{(1)} +
\backslash
underbrace{Z
\backslash
beta}_{(3)} +
\backslash
epsilon$$
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$$Z
\backslash
beta =
\backslash
underbrace{WX_{i_-}
\backslash
beta_1}_{(3a)} +
\backslash
underbrace{X_i
\backslash
beta_2}_{(3b)}$$
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset VSpace 10bp
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In terms of the variables, the model is as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$$dist
\backslash
_clust_i =
\backslash
underbrace{W
\backslash
times (dist
\backslash
_clust
\backslash
hspace{3bp}
\backslash
forall
\backslash
hspace{3bp} j)}_{(1)} +$$
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$$
\backslash
underbrace{SL
\backslash
_EXP
\backslash
_TOTAL + SL
\backslash
_pop
\backslash
_growth + SL
\backslash
_vac
\backslash
_rate}_{(3a)} +$$
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$$
\backslash
underbrace{EXP
\backslash
_TOTAL + pop
\backslash
_growth + pcintgov + pcrev + pcap + }_{(3b)}$$
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$$
\backslash
underbrace{prop
\backslash
_ratio + intensity
\backslash
_stock + EXP
\backslash
_TOTAL*intensity
\backslash
_stock}_{(3b)}$$
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
where 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$i
\backslash
neq j
\backslash
hspace{3bp}
\backslash
forall
\backslash
hspace{3bp} i
\backslash
in S$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$SL
\backslash
_$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 prefix indicates the spatial lag (the average value in the local neighborhood,
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$S$
\end_layout

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To check the face validity of the spatial assumption, one can use a global
 version of the Moran's I calculation defined in Algorithm 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "alg:Local-Moran's-I"

\end_inset

.
 While the global calculation does not permit the identification of hot
 spots, or clusters, within the state, it does have the advantage of providing
 a single statistic that captures the existence of clustering somewhere
 within the state.
 As such, we can evaluate clustering over time more easily.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Moran's-I-dist_clust-yr"

\end_inset

 displays clustering activity in Colorado over time, faceted by six distance
 dimensions.
 The first three (Full Portfolio, Regression Filtered, and Principal Components)
 correspond with the distance measures calculated in the spaces defined
 in Subsection 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Defining-Fiscal-Space"

\end_inset

.
 The second three are transformations of the first three.
 They are change measures that capture the difference in cluster differences
 between the current year (year 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$t$
\end_layout

\end_inset

) and the next year (year 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$t+1$
\end_layout

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Moran's I - Cluster Distance by Year
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Moran's-I-dist_clust-yr"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/ExpDiv_CD_Moran.png
	lyxscale 50
	width 100text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The figure depicts the value of Moran's I for each distance measure by year.
 Higher values indicate clustering of similar values while lower values
 indicate clustering of disimilar values.
 A value of zero should be interpreted as the absence of clustering.
 In other words, the distribution of cluster distances is relatively random
 across counties.
 The color of each observation captures the statistical clarity of the clusterin
g behavior (i.e.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$p$
\end_layout

\end_inset

-value).
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are three properties of the Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Moran's-I-dist_clust-yr"

\end_inset

 that are of particular interest.
 First, the identification of spatial clustering varies dramatically across
 different measures of distance.
 Second, leading change measures are generally less spatially coherent than
 current year absolute measures.
 Third, the current year full portfolio distance measure is the only one
 that seems to exhibit spatial clustering over most of the period, 
\emph on
and that clustering intensity declines over time
\emph default
.
 In short, while it seems as though regional dynamics could play an outsized
 role in causing counties to stray from the behavior of their initial types,
 the data seem to suggest that this expectation is overstated.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Distribution of Distance Measures
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Distribution-of-Distance-Measures"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/ExpDiv_Dist_Distributions.png
	lyxscale 60
	width 100text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the purposes of thoroughness, spatial models were estimated for all
 three distance measures for each year between 1993 and 2009.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Note that cross-sectional spatial models do not easily permit pooled estimation.
 There must be a single value for each variable in each spatial feature.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 As can be seen in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Spatial-Lag-Model"

\end_inset

, these models did not provide consistently clear impacts from the institutional
 variables of interest: COTEL intensity (
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$intensity
\backslash
_stock$
\end_layout

\end_inset

) and the Gallagher ratio (
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$prop
\backslash
_ratio$
\end_layout

\end_inset

).
 In most years, they could not be meaningfully separated from zero.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Spatial Lag Model Results by Year
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Spatial-Lag-Model"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
centerline{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/ExpDiv_SLM_by_year.png
	width 120text%

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
