\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These results clearly lead one to question whether or not the specification
 was appropriate.
 To reiterate, the model sought to capture economic dynamics, tax burden,
 and the impact of activities in the local neighborhood.
 Variations on these themes resulted in similar results to those seen in
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Spatial-Lag-Model"

\end_inset

.
 In light of these findings, an alternative approach was pursued: LASSO
 regression.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
clearpage
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
LASSO Regression
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quotation
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

It has been again and again demonstrated, that those who are accused of
 despising facts and disregarding experience build and profess to build
 wholly upon facts and experience; while those who disavow theory cannot
 make one step without theorizing.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Mill1836"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Mill hints at the natural tension between those at either end of the inquiry
 spectrum, while simultanesouly recognizing that the differences between
 the poles are matters of degree, not concept.
 This is, in fact, an instructive point for the current situation.
 The a priori theoretical relationships hypothesized at the top of this
 section must be converted in an operational specification, which involves
 the selection and form of the variables used to represent said relationships.
 Ultimately, however, transformations can only make so much of a difference.
 In this case, the low explanatory power of the model presented was reasonably
 robust to an array of transformations of the variables presented.
 One must consider the implication: important elements are missing from
 the specification.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fortunately, the context of this analysis is conducive to alternative methods
 of model selection.
 Specifically, a class of estimators has been developed to deal specifically
 with the problem of dealing with a model that contains a number of regressors
 , 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$p$
\end_layout

\end_inset

, that greatly exceeds the number of observations, 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$n$
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 These approaches are referred to as shrinkage, or regularization, methods
 (Algorithm 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "alg:Shrinkage-Methods"

\end_inset

).
 Their utility extends beyond the specific use case for which they were
 designed.
 In general, they are useful for identifying the components of a dataset
 that are the best predictors.
 In contrast to filtering based on pairwise correlation or stepwise variable
 selection, they avoid the primary deficiency with discrete subset selection
 methods: comparatively high variance in predictive accuracy.
 Shrinkage methods rely instead on a continuous process for subset selection.
 In a nutshell, they penalize the sizes of the coefficient estimates.
 Since the loss function must now account for this penalty, the effect is
 to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

shrink
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the estimates down until many of them are no longer meaningfully distinguished
 from zero.
 Those that remain yield effects in spite of the penalty interacted with
 the impacts of all other variables.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float algorithm
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Shrinkage Methods
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "alg:Shrinkage-Methods"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset VSpace 10bp
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$$
\backslash
mathrm{Shrinkage Estimator} = 
\backslash
mathrm{argmin}_{
\backslash
hat{
\backslash
Theta}}
\backslash
{L(
\backslash
Theta,
\backslash
hat{
\backslash
Theta}) + 
\backslash
lambda f(
\backslash
hat{
\backslash
Theta})
\backslash
}$$
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset VSpace 10bp
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center

\series bold
LASSO Implementation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset VSpace 5bp
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$$
\backslash
hat{
\backslash
beta}^{
\backslash
mathrm{LASSO}} = 
\backslash
mathrm{argmin}_{
\backslash
beta} 
\backslash
{
\backslash
frac{1}{2} 
\backslash
sum_{i=1}^N (y_i - 
\backslash
beta_0 - 
\backslash
sum_{j=1}^p x_{i,j}
\backslash
beta_j)^2 + 
\backslash
lambda 
\backslash
sum_{j=1}^p 
\backslash
mid 
\backslash
beta_j 
\backslash
mid 
\backslash
}$$
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset VSpace 5bp
\end_inset

As can be seen, the loss function (
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$L(
\backslash
Theta,
\backslash
hat{
\backslash
Theta})$
\end_layout

\end_inset

) in the LASSO estimator is just ordinary least squares.
 The innovation is in the second term, a penalty that scales with 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$
\backslash
lambda$
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this analysis, following the theoretical specification above with LASSO
 regression provides information that we may use to update the model.
 Furthermore, this approach lessens the chance of omitted variable bias
 (assuming our initial dataset contains a sufficient amount of information).
 Finally, if the institutional variables remain significant, it lends support
 to the main theoretical thrust of this inquiry.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
LASSO Results
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
LASSO estimators can only be run on complete cases.
 Rather than drop the observations for which missing values exist in a few
 variables, the analysis relied on multiple imputation based upon a multivariate
 normal prior.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The joint distribution of all variables was assumed to be normal, and the
 parameters were estimated based upon observed cases.
 The missing values are imputed as draws from this distribution.
 It is for this reason that five imputations were generated.
 Estimates presented here are averages of the estimates across all five
 imputations.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:LASSO-full-avg"

\end_inset

 depicts the impacts of each variable on cluster distance in the full portfolio
 space, averaged across all imputation sets.
 As can be seen, the institutonal variables (
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$intensity
\backslash
_stock$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$prop
\backslash
_ratio$
\end_layout

\end_inset

) still appear to be among the most important drivers of changing fiscal
 behaviors, as measured by distance to the average position of similar counties.
 In fact, most of the theoretical model is contained as a subset of the
 variables identified by the LASSO procedure.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are, however, significant departures from the initial model, most
 notably the impact of the size of government employment.
 Government employment is captured by the proportion of annual payroll in
 a county allocated to the federal (
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$fed
\backslash
_wage$
\end_layout

\end_inset

), state (
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$st
\backslash
_wage$
\end_layout

\end_inset

), and local (
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$loc
\backslash
_wage$
\end_layout

\end_inset

) employees.
 It should also be noted that socioeconomic factors like household size
 (
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$hh
\backslash
_size$
\end_layout

\end_inset

), educational achievement (
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$edu
\backslash
_yrs$
\end_layout

\end_inset

), and current year population growth (
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$pop
\backslash
_growth$
\end_layout

\end_inset

) played meaningful roles as well.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
