\begin_layout Subsection
Panel Analysis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While Subsection 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:ExpDiv-Cross-Sectional-Models"

\end_inset

 has provided useful information regarding plausible drivers of fiscal behavior,
 it is generally advisable to use panel data when possible.
 The increase in the number of observations can increase precision (i.e.
 reduce estimate variance), while leveraging variation across time and space
 can improve accuracy (i.e.
 reduce estimate bias).
 The drawback is that the enhancement techniques leveraged in Subsection
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:ExpDiv-Cross-Sectional-Models"

\end_inset

 are not yet generally available to the best of the author's knowledge.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Developing reliable estimators of the shrinkage type is a task that just
 might exceed the capability of the author.
 Indirect approaches involving the transformation of input data are more
 achievable, but this effort has not been pursued in the context of this
 inquiry.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Furthermore, as will become apparent, the fixed effect techniques used
 here substantially diminish the explained variation in fiscal behavior
 over the pooled case.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To establish why simple reliance on the pooled case may be problematic,
 one can evaluate the behavior of the residuals.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Comparison-of-Residual-behavior"

\end_inset

 compares the distribution of residual values for pooled and fixed effect
 models.
 The separation of central tendency from the zero line in the pooled case
 is a measurement of the bias in the estimates.
 Note that this bias is markedly reduced in the fixed effect case, and variance
 is reduced as well.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Pooled-Residuals-by-county"

\end_inset

 depicts the distributions of residuals by county.
 The implication is that unobserved county-specific effects are distorting
 the estimates from the pooled model.
 In effect, the aspects we do not measure may interact with those that we
 do measure in unexpected ways.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Note that there is also a gradual upward trend in the residuals, but the
 year effect is not nearly as siginificant as the county-specific factors.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Comparison of Residual Distributions
\end_layout

\end_inset

